In 2018, I attended a dinner where the topic was how “AI” how would impact workers. For most of the dinner, everyone focused on how blue-collar workers would be impacted by robotics and automation. Naturally, there was lots of talk about trucking being the #1 job in many states, how it was highly prone to automation, and how we should have a UBI to protect our most vulnerable.

Near the end, someone chimed in that it was **low and mid-level white-collar workers who were most at risk of technological disruption.** This is a somewhat obvious, but often overlooked point.

Is it easier to have a machine / “AI” (i.e., some software) replace your plumber or your paralegal? Your accountant or your construction worker?

Let’s think about how a shift to full remote work will impact salaries specifically for employees in the tech industry.

**How does one survive and thrive in this world?**

-   Be in top % of what you do. A mid-level engineer at Google who whines about cafeteria food might be susceptible to replacement, but [Jeff Dean](https://www.wired.com/story/googles-new-ai-head-is-so-smart-he-doesnt-need-ai/?ref=ryanrodenbaugh.com) doesn't have anything to worry about
-   As Scott Adams has said, develop your [talent stack](https://www.scottadamssays.com/2016/11/28/the-trump-talent-stack/?ref=ryanrodenbaugh.com). This means, you don't have to be Jeff Dean (i.e., the top 1% at something), but you can combine being better than average at several things. For example, maybe you're an OK computer vision engineer and you also have a deep knowledge of fish, you could be uniquely qualified for a job at e.g., [Aquabyte](http://www.aquabyte.ai/index.html?ref=ryanrodenbaugh.com).
-   Have a strong personal brand. People with large audiences who are viewed as "thought leaders" in an industry tend to be well-connected and find it easier to come across new roles. This could take the form of having a popular newsletter, a large Twitter following, or many stars on Github. A software engineer who writes a newsletter about managing engineering teams might have a CEO who reads their work and in turn would jump at the chance to hire them as a manager. A frequent open-source contributor to a project would have an easy time being hired by a company that relies on that software package.
-   Cut your burn and move to a low cost of living geography. Unlike the factory worker that was put out of work, keyboard workers can move to lower CoL geographies and take lower salaries while still living comfortably. It's much easier to [decrease your burn by 3x than to increase your net worth by 3x](https://twitter.com/balajis/status/968236413501124608?s=20&ref=ryanrodenbaugh.com). Instead of paying [$18,000/year](https://www.zillow.com/homedetails/520-Geary-St-511-San-Francisco-CA-94102/2078345539_zpid/?ref=ryanrodenbaugh.com) in rent in San Francisco for a cramped studio apartment in the worst neighborhood, you could pay [$6,000/year](https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/18084726?adults=1&location=Bangkok%2C+Thailand&check_in=2020-10-01&check_out=2020-10-31&display_extensions%5B%5D=MONTHLY_STAYS&source_impression_id=p3_1597254772_U%2B%2BFStNXt19a8BZp&ref=ryanrodenbaugh.com) for a luxury condo rental in Bangkok or a mortgage in the midwest.
